Push local codebase to GitHub (blocked by missing credentials)

Task: Resolve git rebase conflict in favor of local files and push 7 commits to GitHub main branch.

Findings:
- Rebase was already completed before task execution; working tree was clean.
- 7 local commits ahead of origin/main, all ready to push.
- git push origin main --force-with-lease failed with HTTP 128:
  "Invalid username or token. Password authentication is not supported."
- GitHub removed password auth in 2021; a Personal Access Token (PAT) with
  repo scope is required to push via HTTPS.

No code changes were made. The push could not be completed automatically
because credentials are a user-held secret and cannot be stored or injected
by the agent.

Resolution for user:
1. Generate a PAT at github.com/settings/tokens (classic, repo scope)
2. Run: git remote set-url origin https://<TOKEN>@github.com/marksonguarine-sketch/SOFTCODE.git
3. Run: git push origin main --force-with-lease
